  // ... mutates obj at path, returns copy
}
```

### Supabase Schema

The `site_config` table is the same pattern across all standalone client sites:

```sql
CREATE TABLE site_config (
  key TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
  value JSONB NOT NULL,
  updated_at TIMESTAMPTZ DEFAULT NOW()
);
-- Row: { key: "content_overrides", value: { "home": { "hero": { "headline": "...", ... } } } }
```

No per-client table. Single row, single JSONB column. Pattern shared by El Viajero (ej_site_config), Nexa, and DepiFlash.

### When to use this vs the full SaaS path

| Situation | Use this pattern | Use SaaS (multi-tenant-saas-architecture) |
|-----------|-----------------|[REDACTED_TOKEN]|
| Standalone client repo (DepiFlash, Jota Ink) | ✅ Single site, independent deploy | ❌ |
| Builder SaaS (paragu-ai-builder) | ❌ Too manual per tenant | ✅ DB-first with sharded config |
| Need rebuild-free content edits | ✅ Overrides merge at runtime | ✅ Built-in |
| Client has 1-3 sites | ✅ Simple, cheap | ❌ Overengineered |
| Planning 10+ sites | ❌ Doesn't scale | ✅ Design for scale |

## 9. Booking / Calendar Admin (Static-to-Dynamic Feature)

When adding self-booking calendar to a static client brochure site (DepiFlash pattern), the admin needs operational control without a full CRM. Target admin agenda features:

| Feature | Implementation |
|---------|---------------|
| Weekly calendar view (14-day scroll) | Client-side date range + `GET /api/admin/appointments?from=&to=` |
| Confirm / cancel / no-show | `PATCH /api/admin/appointments` with status enum |
| Move appointment | Same PATCH, change `appointment_date` + `start_time` |
| Block full day | `POST /api/admin/blocks` with `block_type=full_day` |
| Block partial hours | `POST /api/admin/blocks` with `block_type=partial_day` + start_time/end_time |
| Delete block | `DELETE /api/admin/blocks?id=uuid` |
| Edit business hours | `PUT /api/admin/hours` with full 7-day array |
| View blocked dates | `GET /api/admin/blocks` |

### Admin API Architecture

```typescript
// All admin routes sit under /api/admin/<resource>
// Auth via PIN header (simple, works server-side without Supabase auth):
export function isAdminRequest(request: Request) {
  const pin = process.env.DEPIFLASH_ADMIN_PIN || process.env.ADMIN_PIN || ""
  if (!pin) return true // no pin set = open access
  return request.headers.get("x-admin-pin") === pin ||
         request.headers.get("authorization") === `Bearer ${pin}`
}

// Public booking routes are OUTSIDE /api/admin/ to keep middleware clean:
//   /api/availability (GET)
//   /api/appointments (POST)
```

### Admin PIN UX

Store the PIN in `localStorage` so it survives page refreshes:

```tsx
useEffect(() => { setPin(localStorage.getItem("depiflash_admin_pin") || "") }, [])
useEffect(() => { if (pin) localStorage.setItem("depiflash_admin_pin", pin) }, [pin])

const headers = useMemo<HeadersInit>(() => {
  const base: Record<string, string> = { "Content-Type": "application/json" }
  if (pin) base["x-admin-pin"] = pin
  return base
}, [pin])
```

### Admin Sidebar Entry in Static Sites

For sites with an admin content editor (`/admin/content`), add the agenda link there or create a simple standalone page at `/admin/agenda` with navigation back to content.

### Pitfall: TypeScript headers union types

When using `useMemo` with conditional headers, TypeScript infers a union type (`{ x-admin-pin: string } | { x-admin-pin?: undefined }`) that `fetch()` rejects. Fix: `useMemo<HeadersInit>(() => { const base: Record<string, string> = { "Content-Type": "application/json" }; if (pin) base["x-admin-pin"] = pin; return base; }, [pin])`.

